text: Fancy looking place situated on a very conveniently located street corner. That's the good part. The inside is spacious and was not very busy when I visited the place. There were some tourists going through the obligatory ritual of purchasing coffee beans for the hoi polloi back home. You place your order at the counter and are given a number along with your receipt. Then you sit at a table and wait for your order to be served. The staff seemed busy with themselves, guess there's not much you can do on a quiet evening. I ordered the latte as I have done with the rest of the cafes I frequented during my visit. It's easy to compare the taste and prices across the board. Can't understand why some of the other reviewers are making such a fuss about the coffee here! It's not what it's made out to be and is OVERPRICED! Walk over a few steps down the road and there is a cafe that serves better tastier latte at a much better price and one of the best street views you could hope to find anywhere in Asia!

text: Trung Nguyen Legend Coffee at 80 Dong Khoi, City. Ho Chi Minh, received many compliments for coffee quality and space. This is a popular spot for a variety of Vietnamese coffees, including the signature Legend coffee made from weasel coffee beans. Prices range from 60,000 to 110,000 VND  The shop has a lively but not noisy space, creating a comfortable feeling for customers to enjoy coffee in the traditional Vietnamese way.  The location of the restaurant is convenient, located on busy Dong Khoi street, near many luxury hotels.  Customers appreciate the dedicated service and menus available in both Vietnamese and English, enhancing the overall experience.  For those unfamiliar with Vietnamese coffee, the shop staff will provide images and detailed explanations to help customers easily choose.  Overall, Trung Nguyen Legend Coffee at 80 Dong Khoi is a recommended place for both coffee lovers and those who want to experience Vietnamese coffee culture in a friendly space.

Away from Vietnam's bitter Robusta style It mainly produces the soft taste of Arabica blinding.  I recommend two coffee menus, The 1st is an "Energy" and the 2nd is a "L'amour" which are disappeared in menu before corona. Particularly recommended menu items are: Energy and Weasel Ruak It's L'amour, but it was discontinued before Corona.  But they sell "Energy" which is luwak, farm weseal coffee by whole roasted coffee bean. It tastes like strong milky flavor and soft body, silky aftertasting. However, ‚ÄúEnergy‚Äù only sells coffee beans. Although it is Farm luwak, it has a strong milky scent. I like the soft body and silky aftertaste.  And in case of L'amore, they still sell it but different menu name. So if you show picture of L'amour then they will make it for you. L'amour isn't on the menu either. Show me a picture of the coffee and they will make it for you.  L'amour is made of espresso and soft cream, sinamon flavor, baked nuts...etc.. It looks like almost con panna.. It is severed by small espresso coffee cup. It tastes like korean instant coffee "maxin gold" but 10 time more good strong flavor. L'amour is espresso with cream and It's like con panna with less cream and cinnamon flavor and nuts. It comes in a small espresso cup. The taste is 10 times the taste of Korean Maxim Gold.  It's picture is on my reviews. The photo of L'amour is among my review photos.  They make coffee with vietnamese traditional hand drip tool, "Phin" like meltlita method. Coffee is mainly called phin in Vietnam. Extracted using a traditional immersion hand drip tool.  Phin tool is the best method to make coffee with robusta coffee bean. The pin can extract the most delicious robusta.  Bon voyage a saigon Then have a nice trip to Saigon.

place_name: Th·∫ø Gi·ªõi C√† Ph√™ Trung Nguy√™n Legend
text: Legend Coffee is a Vietnamese Finn coffee that uses Konsak coffee beans. If you pour it into a pin with hot water and wait for about 5 minutes, the water will come out. After that, you can mix it with hot water, condensed milk, or mix it with ice and drink it.  I recommend ordering it iced. If you eat it on its own, it's almost like espresso, so it's difficult to eat, and the ice + condensed milk combination is better than mixing it with hot water.  I was thinking of buying a pin dripper, but I couldn't because they didn't sell anything other than a package that included coffee beans for about 100,000 won.  Legend Coffee has a very nice scent, with a subtle peanut butter-like scent. Even if you drink it cold or hot, the scent does not go away. 4 stars considering the price
